<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1437,1193,1758]" box="[199,710,1301,1326]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
Published figures: 
<bibRefCitation author="Nekrutenko" box="[409,705,1301,1326]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" refString="Nekrutenko, Y. P. (1965) Tertiary nymphalid butterflies and some phylogenetic aspects of systematic lepidopterology. Journal of Research on the Lepidoptera, 4, 149 - 158." type="journal article" year="1965">
Nekrutenko (1965: 
<figureCitation box="[628,696,1301,1326]" captionStart="FIGURES 3 – 4" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1801,1823]" captionTargetBox="[165,1429,840,1774]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[154,1438,828,1788]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 3 – 4. Wing venation of (A) Pareronia Bingham, 1907 (Pieridae), and (B) Hasora Moore, 1881 (Hesperiidae). See text for explanation." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/583186/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
)
</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1437,1193,1758]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
Fragment of hindwing only. Judging from Nekrutenko’s figure (1965: 
<figureCitation box="[1004,1066,1337,1362]" captionStart="FIGURES 3 – 4" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1801,1823]" captionTargetBox="[165,1429,840,1774]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[154,1438,828,1788]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 3 – 4. Wing venation of (A) Pareronia Bingham, 1907 (Pieridae), and (B) Hasora Moore, 1881 (Hesperiidae). See text for explanation." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/583186/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Fig 4</figureCitation>
) the cell is open, an apomorphy found (but not exclusively) in many 
<taxonomicName box="[585,740,1373,1398]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Nymphalinae">Nymphalinae</taxonomicName>
. However, the author considered the fossil congeneric with 
<taxonomicName authority="Linnaeus" authorityName="Linnaeus" box="[151,479,1409,1434]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Vanessa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atalanta">
<emphasis box="[151,345,1409,1434]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Vanessa atalanta</emphasis>
(Linnaeus)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Linnaeus" authorityName="Linnaeus" box="[494,797,1409,1434]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Cynthia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cardui">
<emphasis box="[494,665,1409,1434]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Cynthia cardui</emphasis>
(Linnaeus)
</taxonomicName>
(considered to belong to the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[1220,1310,1410,1433]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Vanessa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1220,1310,1410,1433]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Vanessa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
now), etc. (
<taxonomicName box="[158,315,1445,1470]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Nymphalinae">Nymphalinae</taxonomicName>
), where the cell is closed, though the cross vein may be weak. Because of some proportional similarities, he suggested a close relationship with 
<taxonomicName box="[717,822,1481,1506]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Cynthia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cardui">
<emphasis box="[717,822,1481,1506]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">C. cardui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, although he admitted that the material is not complete enough for a reliable identification. He described the fossil under the “nomen conditionalis”, 
<taxonomicName box="[1216,1408,1517,1542]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Pyrameis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fossilis">
<emphasis box="[1216,1408,1517,1542]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Pyrameis fossilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a term not recognized by the International Code of Zoological Nomenclature. I found different venational proportions in the species from those mentioned by Nekrutenko. The proportions may be variable and not a reliable guide for relationship. The venational arrangement as far as visible in the fossil is found in many extant nymphalines and it is of little help in establishing closer relationships. In view of the deficient useful characters in the fossil I wonder why 
<bibRefCitation author="Kozlov" box="[430,596,1697,1722]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" refString="Kozlov, M. V. (1988) Paleontology of lepidopterans and problems of the phylogeny of the order Papilionida. In: Ponomarenko, A. G. (Ed.), The Mesozoic-Cenozoic Crisis in the Evolution of Insects. Academy of Sciences, Moscow, pp. 16 - 69. [in Russian]" type="book chapter" year="1988">Kozlov (1988)</bibRefCitation>
synonimized it with 
<taxonomicName authority="Miller &amp; Brown" authorityName="Miller &amp; Brown" box="[838,1258,1697,1722]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Vanessa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amerindica">
<emphasis box="[838,1065,1697,1722]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Vanessa amerindica</emphasis>
Miller &amp; Brown
</taxonomicName>
(see comments above).
</paragraph>
